    sanskrit: "अमी हि त्वां सुरसङ्घा विशन्ति \nकेचिद्भीताः प्राञ्जलयो गृणन्ति |\nस्वस्तीत्युक्त्वा महर्षिसिद्धसङ्घाः \nस्तुवन्ति त्वां स्तुतिभिः पुष्कलाभिः ||",
    transliteration: "amī hi tvāṁ sura-saṅghā viśhanti kechid bhītāḥ prāñjalayo gṛiṇanti\nsvastīty uktvā maharṣi-siddha-saṅghāḥ stuvanti tvāṁ stutibhiḥ puṣhkalābhiḥ",
    translation: "All the hosts of demigods are entering into You; some are afraid and offer prayers, while sages praise You with hymns.",
    purport: `
        <p><strong>1. Dual Response to the Same Reality:</strong> The same universal form evokes completely different reactions—fear in some, reverence in others. This reveals that the Divine does not change; it is the observer’s state of consciousness that determines the experience. Those attached to stability feel threatened, while those aligned with truth respond with surrender and praise.</p>

        <p><strong>2. Entry into the Divine:</strong> The phrase <em>viśhanti</em> (entering into You) suggests that all beings are not merely observing but moving toward dissolution or integration within this vast presence. It indicates that existence itself is flowing back into its source, whether consciously or unconsciously.</p>

        <p><strong>3. Hierarchy of Perception:</strong> Sages and realized beings respond with composed praise, while others are overwhelmed. This shows that deeper understanding does not eliminate intensity but transforms fear into recognition. Knowledge refines the response to reality.</p>

        <p><strong>Conclusion:</strong> This verse reveals that reality is experienced differently based on inner alignment. The same truth can be terrifying or liberating depending on one’s awareness. It emphasizes that the journey is not about changing reality, but about transforming perception so that one can face the infinite without fear.</p>
    `
